{"recommendationid": "132666822", "author": {"steamid": "76561197996884202", "num_games_owned": 0, "num_reviews": 5, "playtime_forever": 26825, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 7, "playtime_at_review": 3620, "last_played": 1764281667}, "language": "english", "review": "Forget all the half-arsed reviews along the lines of "Wah wah wah, Ubisoft are big and nasty and they stole my lunch money..."  Watch Dogs: Legion is an amazingly polished game.  As a Londoner, it's a treat to actually stand in places I've been in real life, and the London of WD:L is a chillingly realistic future possibility.  The five major villains (count 'em) are various degrees of monstrous,  and the plot is clever and well realised.   Bagley, DedSec's friendly AI, is sardonic, sarcastic and caustic but always lovable, and each recruit you add to the roster (and yes, you can recruit literally anyone) soon acquires their own personality, helped by some spot-on voice acting which really helps reflect the wonderful multi-culturalism of London.  I've just finished my first play-through and I immediately want to go again - it's that good.  I do recommend you go with perma-death on though; the stakes are so much higher when your operatives can die on missions.  

Wait for WD:L on sale if you like (and there's probably no reason not to), but do buy it.  You won't regret it.

Oh and yes, there are micro-transactions if you want to go there - this is Ubisoft - but they are tucked away in a corner of the team menu and can safely be ignored.  Nothing you can buy there is in any way essential to the game.", "timestamp_created": 1676162216, "timestamp_updated": 1676162216, "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "weighted_vote_score": 0.5, "comment_count": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": false, "primarily_steam_deck": false}

